            "content": "This is one of the most common dilemmas facing Green Valley homeowners with aging heating systems. Use this decision framework to make the right choice for your situation. Repair if: Your furnace is under 10 years old (likely has substantial remaining life), repair cost is under $400 (relatively minor issue), system has been well-maintained with regular tune-ups (extends life significantly), you're planning to move within 1-2 years (replacement won't benefit you long enough), repair addresses a single component failure (igniter, flame sensor, capacitor), and the system has good repair history with no major failures. Typical affordable repairs include igniter replacement ($180-280), flame sensor cleaning/replacement ($95-195), blower motor capacitor ($145-225), thermostat replacement ($120-280), and limit switch replacement ($165-245). Replace if: Your furnace is over 15 years old AND repair cost exceeds $600-800 (combination indicates end-of-life), system has required multiple repairs in past 2-3 years (declining reliability), you're experiencing rising energy bills despite similar usage (declining efficiency), furnace requires major component replacement (heat exchanger $1,500-2,400, blower motor $650-950, gas valve $600-900, control board $450-750), system is oversized or undersized for your home (improper sizing wastes energy), you're planning to stay in your home 5+ years (replacement investment pays off), or you want to upgrade to higher efficiency for lower operating costs and rebates/tax credits. Special considerations for Green Valley retirees: Factor in peace of mind value—avoiding mid-winter breakdown stress may be worth investment even if repair/replace economics are marginal. Consider health and mobility—if a winter heating outage would be especially difficult or dangerous for health conditions, err toward replacement and reliability. Evaluate total housing costs—if heating replacement eliminates ongoing repair concerns, maintenance becomes simpler and more predictable. Factor in home sale timeline—if you plan to sell within 5-7 years for downsizing or assisted living, a new heating system adds measurable value and appeal to buyers. Action step: Request detailed analysis from your technician including repair cost versus replacement cost, remaining useful life estimate, energy cost comparison (current system versus high-efficiency replacement), available rebates and financing, and 5-year total cost of ownership comparison for informed decision-making."
